          "text": "Implement the following plan:\n\n# In-Memory HLS Segment Cache\n\n## Context\nCurrently FFmpeg writes `.ts` segments to disk, and Go's `http.FileServer` serves them. Every viewer request hits disk I/O (or OS page cache at best). For a streaming server, we want segments served from RAM — zero disk reads in the hot path.\n\n## Memory Budget\n\nSegment sizes (2-second segments at configured bitrates):\n\n| Quality | Bitrate | ~Segment Size |\n|---------|---------|---------------|\n| 2160p   | 20.2 Mbps | ~5.0 MB |\n| 1440p   | 12.2 Mbps | ~3.0 MB |\n| 1080p   | 6.1 Mbps  | ~1.5 MB |\n| 720p    | 4.1 Mbps  | ~1.0 MB |\n| 480p    | 1.6 Mbps  | ~400 KB |\n| 360p    | 0.7 Mbps  | ~165 KB |\n\nFFmpeg keeps `hls_list_size=5` segments in the playlist. The cleaner removes segments >60s old. We should cache enough to cover the playlist window plus a buffer.\n\n**Cache 10 segments per quality** (covers playlist + stragglers):\n\n- Default (1080p+720p+480p+360p): ~30 MB\n- All 6 qualities: ~110 MB\n- With `HLS_CACHE_MB` env var to cap it (default: 128 MB)\n\n## Architecture\n\n### New file: `internal/hls/cache.go`\n\nA `SegmentCache` that uses `fsnotify` to watch the HLS directory for new/deleted `.ts` and `.m3u8` files, loading them into memory automatically.\n\n```\nFFmpeg writes to disk\n        ↓\n   fsnotify CREATE event\n        ↓\n   Cache reads file into []byte\n        ↓\n   Viewer requests segment\n        ↓\n   Handler serves from cache (no disk read)\n        ↓\n   fsnotify REMOVE event (or cleaner removes)\n        ↓\n   Cache evicts entry\n```\n\n**Why fsnotify instead of polling:** Instant reaction to new segments, no latency gap between FFmpeg writing and cache having the data. Efficient — no periodic scans.\n\n### Cache structure\n\n```go\ntype SegmentCache struct {\n    mu       sync.RWMutex\n    entries  map[string]cacheEntry  // key: relative path like \"720p/seg001.ts\"\n    size     int64                  // current total bytes\n    maxSize  int64                  // from HLS_CACHE_MB\n    watcher  *fsnotify.Watcher\n    hlsDir   string\n}\n\ntype cacheEntry struct {\n    data    []byte\n    modTime time.Time\n}\n```\n\n### Serving flow\n\nThe HLS handler will check the cache first. Cache hit → serve from RAM. Cache miss → fall back to disk (for edge cases like startup race).\n\nPlaylists (`.m3u8`) are also cached — they're tiny (~2KB) but requested every 2s by every viewer.\n\n## Files to modify\n\n### New files\n1. **`internal/hls/cache.go`** — `SegmentCache` with fsnotify watcher, `Get(path)`, auto-load on CREATE, auto-evict on REMOVE. If cache is full, evict oldest entries by modTime.\n\n### Modified files\n2. **`internal/hls/handler.go`** — `Handler` takes a `*SegmentCache`. `serveHLS()` checks cache first, falls back to disk. Remove `fs http.Handler` field.\n3. **`internal/hls/cleaner.go`** — No changes needed. Cleaner deletes from disk → fsnotify fires REMOVE → cache evicts. Cleaner also purges entries from cache that exist in memory but not on disk (safety net).\n4. **`internal/config/config.go`** — Add `HLSCacheMB int` field (env `HLS_CACHE_MB`, default `128`)\n5. **`cmd/server/main.go`** — Create `SegmentCache`, pass to `hls.NewHandler`, start/stop watcher with context\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n### `cache.go`\n\n```go\nfunc NewSegmentCache(hlsDir string, maxSizeMB int) (*SegmentCache, error)\nfunc (c *SegmentCache) Start(ctx context.Context) error   // starts fsnotify watcher goroutine\nfunc (c *SegmentCache) Get(relPath string) ([]byte, time.Time, bool)  // returns data, modTime, ok\n```\n\n**fsnotify watcher goroutine:**\n- On CREATE/WRITE of `.ts` or `.m3u8`: read file, store in map. If over maxSize, evict oldest `.ts` entries.\n- On REMOVE of `.ts` or `.m3u8`: delete from map.\n- Watch all quality subdirs (add watches dynamically).\n\n**Eviction:** When `size > maxSize`, remove oldest `.ts` entries (by modTime) until under limit. Never evict `.m3u8` files — they're tiny and critical.\n\n### `handler.go` changes\n\nReplace `http.FileServer` with custom serve logic:\n```go\nfunc (h *Handler) serveHLS() http.Handler {\n    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n        // ... CORS headers (same as now) ...\n\n        relPath := strings.TrimPrefix(r.URL.Path, \"/live/\")\n\n        // Try cache first\n        if data, modTime, ok := h.cache.Get(relPath); ok {\n            // Set content type based on extension\n            http.ServeContent(w, r, relPath, modTime, bytes.NewReader(data))\n            return\n        }\n\n        // Fallback to disk\n        // ... existing file server logic ...\n    })\n}\n```\n\nUsing `http.ServeContent` gives us proper Range request support, ETag, and If-Modified-Since handling for free.\n\n### `config.go` addition\n\n```go\nHLSCacheMB: getEnvInt(\"HLS_CACHE_MB\", 128),\n```\n\n### `main.go` wiring\n\n```go\nsegmentCache, err := hls.NewSegmentCache(cfg.HLSDir, cfg.HLSCacheMB)\n// ... error handling ...\ngo segmentCache.Start(ctx)  // starts fsnotify watcher\n\nhlsHandler := hls.NewHandler(cfg.HLSDir, segmentCache)\n```\n\n## Dependencies\n\nNeed to add `github.com/fsnotify/fsnotify` — the standard Go file watching library (used by cobra/viper, Hugo, etc.). Pure Go, no CGO.\n\n## Verification\n\n```bash\ngo build ./...\ngo test ./internal/hls/...\n```\n\n- Start server, start stream\n- Open player — segments should be served from cache (check with debug logging)\n- Cache memory should stay within `HLS_CACHE_MB` limit\n- Stopping stream → segments cleaned → cache empties\n- Server restart with no stream → cache is empty, no crash\n\n\nIf you need specific details from before exiting plan mode (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /Users/m.ovchinnikov/.claude/projects/-Users-m-ovchinnikov-GolandProjects-twitch-desent/128f7d1a-9b3b-454f-805c-498e9e501825.jsonl",
